  stimulus_text = 'The 1960s saw a flowering of experimental poetry. Poets in this period were not content to simply record their observations; they wanted to challenge readers’ expectations of what poetry could be. As a result, poets began to experiment with form and style, often using unconventional techniques and language.  One such poet was E. E. Cummings, whose poems are known for their unconventional use of punctuation and capitalization. For example, the poem "i sing of Olaf glad and big" features lines that are not only broken up in unexpected ways but also contain words that are run together without spaces. "i carry your heart with me(i carry it in
